"nl":{"Abt 1240–1304":"circa 1240–1304","1240–Male":"1240–Overleden","1280–Male":"1280–Overleden","1284–1335":"1284–1335","1286–Male":"1286–Overleden","1288–Male":"1288–Overleden","1240–1304":"1240–1304","Abt 1240":"circa 1240","1304":"1304","about 1280":"circa 1280","1259":"1259","1335":"1335","1288":"1288","1286":"1286","1284":"1284","1240":"1240","1280":"1280","<1286>":"1286","1290":"1290","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Aske, Easby, Yorkshire, England":"Aske, Easby, Yorkshire, England","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Aske Manor, Yorkshire, England":"Manor, Yorkshire, England","Wele-juxta-Beverley, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"Abt 1240–1304":"about 1240–1304","1240–Male":"1240–Deceased","1280–Male":"1280–Deceased","1284–1335":"1284–1335","1286–Male":"1286–Deceased","1288–Male":"1288–Deceased","1240–1304":"1240–1304","Abt 1240":"about 1240","1304":"1304","about 1280":"about 1280","1259":"1259","1335":"1335","1288":"1288","1286":"1286","1284":"1284","1240":"1240","1280":"1280","<1286>":"1286","1290":"1290","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Aske, Easby, Yorkshire, England":"Aske, Easby, Yorkshire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Aske Manor, Yorkshire, England":"Manor, Yorkshire, England","Wele-juxta-Beverley, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cecilia","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin name <i>Caecilia</i>, feminine form of <i>Caecilius</i> (  see  Cecil  ). This was a good deal more common than the masculine form, largely due to the fame of the 2nd- or 3rd-century virgin martyr whose name is still mentioned daily in the Roman Catholic Canon of the Mass. She is regarded as the patron saint of music and has inspired works such as  Purcell's  ‘Ode on St Cecilia's Day’, although the reasons for this association are not clear."],"variants":[{"name":"Cecelia","meanings":["From the Latin name <i>Caecilia</i>, feminine form of <i>Caecilius</i> (  see  Cecil  ). This was a good deal more common than the masculine form, largely due to the fame of the 2nd- or 3rd-century virgin martyr whose name is still mentioned daily in the Roman Catholic Canon of the Mass. She is regarded as the patron saint of music and has inspired works such as  Purcell's  ‘Ode on St Cecilia's Day’, although the reasons for this association are not clear."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"England","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Middle English <i>Engelond</i> ‘England’. It was probably a formal alternative to   English  , which is also well evidenced as a surname in England. These names may have been acquired by English landowners who moved in Norman social circles or who lived in a neighbouring country (Scotland, Wales, or Ireland), or by English merchants who traded abroad.","Norwegian: habitational name from any of various farmsteads so named, from Old Norse <i>eng</i> ‘meadow’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’.","Swedish: ornamental name with the same meaning as 2."],"variants":[{"name":"English","meanings":["English, Scottish, and Welsh: ethnic name from Middle English <i>English</i>, <i>Inglish</i>, <i>Inglis</i> ‘English’ (Old English <i>Englisc</i>), sometimes alternating with Anglo-Norman French <i>Engleis</i>, <i>Engles</i>, <i>Anglais</i>, <i>Angles</i> (Old French <i>Englois</i>). Compare   Inglis   and   England  . Among the aristocracy and upper gentry it marked out a man of English ancestry from one of Norman or continental origin. In counties bordering England with Scotland and Wales the name distinguished an Englishman from a Scot or a native Welshman on both sides of the border. The name may also have been acquired by English merchants who traded abroad or who lived and worked in a ‘French’ borough in England (one exclusively administered by Normans).","Irish: in Ireland, this name was used to denote an Englishman, often being adopted for Irish <b>Aingléis</b> ‘Englishman’ or through mistranslation for <b>Mac an Ghallóglaigh</b>, see   Gallogly   and   Golightly  ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":19,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705190,"age":50,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Cecilia of England was born about 1240, in England, United Kingdom. She married Hugh de Aske in Aske, Easby, Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. She died in 1304, in Yorkshire, England, at the age of 65."},"et":{"Abt 1240–1304":"umbes 1240–1304","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1280–Male":"1280–Surnud","1284–1335":"1284–1335","1286–Male":"1286–Surnud","1288–Male":"1288–Surnud","1240–1304":"1240–1304","Abt 1240":"umbes 1240","1304":"1304","about 1280":"umbes 1280","1259":"1259","1335":"1335","1288":"1288","1286":"1286","1284":"1284","1240":"1240","1280":"1280","<1286>":"1286","1290":"1290","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Aske, Easby, Yorkshire, England":"Aske, Easby, Yorkshire, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Aske Manor, Yorkshire, England":"Manor, Yorkshire, England","Wele-juxta-Beverley, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1240–1304":"noin 1240–1304","124